_data.body:
We just finished our **Summer Term 21** with incredible results. We'll post soon the recording of the final event on YouTube.

And if you want to know more about the upcoming **Winter Term 21/22**, do [subscribe to our newsletter](https://bln.techlabs.org/newsletter). We should announce dates soon!

questions.title: Where can I find the courses?
questions.content: See #codeathome announcements for the link to our learning platform edyoucated.

questions.title: Am I supposed to receive a personalized track? Why is there a survey?
questions.content: For the #codeathome Bootcamp, we don't offer any tailored tracks due to the intense and relatively short learning phase. You can select between the four different tracks (Web Development, UX/UI, Data Science, and AI). We only offer personalized tracks for the local programs, to fill out the survey is only needed there.

questions.title: When should I start working on the online courses? Are there any fix lessons?
questions.content: We recommend to start as early as possible to be able to finish your track in approximately 6 weeks, in order to have enough time to work on your project. There aren't any regular lessons, you have full flexibility and control over your learning time and can decide when you want to work on your learning track(s). However, we have set learning milestones, which you can use to orientate yourself.

questions.title: Is there a Deadline to complete the tracks?
questions.content: You have to complete your track(s) by the 31st of October to get a certificate.

questions.title: How much time do I have to study?
questions.content: We recommend to study 6-10 hours per week on your track.

questions.title: Is it possible to do more than one track within the nine weeks ?
questions.content: Yes it is. Theoretically you can do all four tracks if you have enough time. However, we recommend focusing on one track at a time in order to deepen your knowledge and understanding of the topic. Join us again in the next #codeathome Bootcamp batch to develop your digital skills in a different field! Sign up for the newsletter and stay informed.

questions.title: How will I get to know the other participants?
questions.content:
We have a vibrant slack community in which you will be invited. Furthermore, you will be grouped with 3-5 other Techies from your track. Together with your TrackStudy-Buddies, you can study, have remote coffees, and apply for the project phase. 
(See also Project Phase: During the project phase, you will work in a diverse team and solve a societal challenge with your newly developed tech skills. This is where you will definitely get in touch with your fellow learners, learn from each other, and build a great product!)

questions.title: Who are my TrackStudy-Buddies and when will I meet them?
questions.content: We will pair you with 3-5 other Techies studying the same main track during the first week. Together with your TrackStudy-Buddies, you can study, have remote coffees, and work together during the project phase. We will create a private Slack channel for you and your TrackStudy-Buddies, where you can meet remotely.

questions.title: Are the Tracks still accessible after the nine weeks?
questions.content: Yes, you will have access to edyoucated after the #codeathome Bootcamp. But have in mind that we recommend finish your track(s) by 31 October.

questions.title: Will I get a certificate for each track?
questions.content: You will get a certificate for each completed track. Also you have to hand in one solution with your project team - not one for each track, just one for all!

questions.title: What is the Project Phase?
questions.content:
During the Project Phase (05 October - 31 October), you will work in a diverse team (3-5 people) and solve a societal challenge with your newly developed tech skills. You have the chance to consolidate and apply what you have learned. This is where you will definitely get in touch with your fellow learners, learn from each other and build a great product!
For more information check out our üèîÔ∏è [#codeathome Project Guide](https://www.notion.so/techlabs/codeathome-Project-Guide-119f2e2ac19842569bf6ca862abfe3cd).

questions.title: When and how can I find my team mates?
questions.content:
You will be grouped with 3-5 other Techies from your track at the end of the first week of the #codeathome Bootcamp. You and your TrackStudy-Buddies can register for the Project Phase (at least 3 people).
If you lose your TrackStudy-Buddies, or you want to work with other Techies, you can also apply as an individual (We will make an announcement in Slack!). Those who sign up as individuals will be formed into teams by us to ensure diverse backgrounds and a good mixture of advanced techies and beginners.

questions.title: Is the project phase mandatory?
questions.content:
To receive the #codeathome Bootcamp Certificate, you must have to:
1. Complete 75% of your online-learning Track(s) on edyoucated (by the 31st of October) 
2. Submit a solution with your project team (also by the 31st of October).

questions.title: How much time do I have to block?
questions.content: To ensure successful outcomes,¬†we kindly ask you to already block some time during the project phase to work on your project and meet virtually with your team. We estimate that you need between 5¬†and 10¬†hours per week depending on your chosen project.

questions.title: Are my tech skills sufficient when the Project Phase starts?
questions.content: Totally! We ensure a good mixture of advanced techies and newbies in the teams. In addition, TechLabs Mentors will support you during this phase.

questions.title: I haven't finished the online-learning of my track until the project phase starts, are my tech skills sufficient yet?
questions.content: Yes, of course! We encourage you to have at least 60% of your online-learning done when the Project Phase starts. You can continue learning while working with your project team. We recommend to finish online-learning as early as possible, so you can fully concentrate on your project work and the submission in the last weeks.

questions.title: Why does the Project Phase start next to the online-learning?
questions.content: We want to give you and your team enough time for working on your project, get to know each other, and set up a remote project working environment. We recommend finishing the online-learning until week 6 so that you can focus on the project work henceforth.

questions.title: How should we start and find a project idea?
questions.content:
We will give you an overall topic for the Project Phase, as a frame. Together with your team, you will come up with an idea: Conduct a Design Thinking workshop, brainstorm or create a mind map together in order to elaborate ideas. With your project idea, you and your team mates can register for the Project Phase in week 5. We will keep you informed about the timing and deadlines in our Slack announcements channel.
For inspiration check out our üèîÔ∏è [#codeathome Project Guide](https://www.notion.so/techlabs/codeathome-Project-Guide-119f2e2ac19842569bf6ca862abfe3cd) and the TechLabs [@Ideation Guide](https://www.notion.so/Ideation-Guide-7f59cf768f2a45c4a86a02b29d121cd9).

questions.title: Will we get any help during the time?
questions.content:
Yes, our mentors are still there for you and will support you and your project team. 
Furthermore, you and your team mates can get the chance to pitch your project idea during a wednesday social event. This is your opportunity to get some valuable feedback. More information will be posted in Slack.
Also check out our resources page for help üì¶ [Resources](https://www.notion.so/techlabs/Journey-Timeline-Website-df262f989af34e4d84c8b13ecafb0241#4ebe07a2944943ab85838dc8763ba353).

questions.title: How and when do we have to submit our solutions?
questions.content: We will provide a submission template.¬†The solutions have to be submitted in English by the 31st of October 2020, 11 PM CEST¬†as a presentation video, ppt, demo, prototype, git hub code (depending on your solution).

questions.title: Are there any winners?
questions.content: All of you are winners. However, we will announce the winners and an overall winner during our closing ceremony in November.

questions.title: What are the evaluation criteria for the solutions?
questions.content: The main criteria are listed here: üèÖ [Evaluation Criteria](https://www.notion.so/techlabs/Evaluation-Criteria-codeathome-II-5a1c05f1154f496c94bcd72a47bfbc1e)

items.title: Reinventing Education
items.description: Education and technology has been in a race since the invention of printing.  Today, education is lagging behind, says David Middelbeck.  We need to change the fundamentals of learning to adapt to the digital age.  David tells his story of how after learning in Muenster and Harvard, he has just left a good job in tech to help bring technology into education. David Middelbeck stands up for a world without digital illiterates as the Chairman of the European nonprofit organization TechLabs. He co-founded the organization 2 years ago in M√ºnster, and now helps hundreds of students every year to learn coding skills at its three locations in M√ºnster, Barcelona & Copenhagen.

items.title: TECHLABS x USA | A Journey Into Silicon Valley | The Aftermovie
items.description: TechLabs M√ºnster, Germany teamed up to bring the TechLabs' ways of digital education to the US. Over 2 weeks they had exciting meetings with tech leaders like AirBnb, attended interesting conferences and got to try out the most recent innovations in the San Francisco bay area. They met extremely talented people and bright minds that were curious about the TechLabs mission of universal digital education.

_data.title: Git Workshop
_data.description:
In our 3h interactive Git Workshop we will teach you all the Git skills you need for your upcoming project phase.

Git is a tool which allows you to create save points of the current status of your project and return back to it anytime. Git allows you to play around with your code, without being worried to break it!
Even better: This does not only work alone, but also working together with other people! Git (& our used online service GitHub) is designed in a way that multiple people can work on a project at the same time easily.

We **strongly recommend** to attend this session, to be able to use Git, since TechLabs requires the usage of Git from all Techies during the project phase. It will be an interactive workshop of 3h.

We really want to give you the best experience for learning Git, so we put in the effort to create an interactive workshop, where we will teach you the skills and then give you the chance to practice them in breakout rooms guided by our mentors. To not waste time on installation, Git needs to be installed and set up properly to be used for the workshop! For setting up and testing if you configured everything we require everyone who wants to attend to follow the preperation steps **until Friday the 16th of April 4pm**:

_data.title: Lightning Talk #2: Human Rights & Design Thinking
_data.description:
In this talk, __Charlotte Seiler__ and __Vanessa Giersdorf__ ([Getting There Consulting](https://www.gettingthere-consulting.com/)) will introduce their Human Rights-Centered Design approach and apply this to the subject of AI.

As Artificial Intelligence evolves, so do the many controversies that surround the use of this advanced technology. It is therefore crucial to understand its impact on a societal and public policy level. Scenarios in problem areas: privacy, explainability, reliability and risks of complex systems, responsibility of professionals for applications and consequences of their work.

Charlotte and Vanessa believe that data science and machine learning can help us design intelligent products, services, and systems that improve people‚Äôs everyday lives. But in order to have a truly positive impact, AI-powered technologies must be grounded in human rights and work to extend and enhance our capabilities, not replace them.
